					<description><![CDATA[<p>Spiro has raised a landmark $215 million equity investment to supercharge its pan-African expansion. This significant investment will drive Spiro&#8217;s pan-African expansion, accelerating your operations with capital for localised manufacturing,</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/spiro-raises-215m-for-africa-ev-expansion/" data-wpel-link="internal">Spiro Raises $215M for Africa EV Expansion</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://www.spironet.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">Spiro </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">has raised a landmark $215 million equity </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/endra-raises-50m-to-automate-data-centre-design/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">investment </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">to supercharge its pan-African expansion. This significant investment will drive Spiro&#8217;s pan-African expansion, accelerating your operations with capital for localised manufacturing, EV infrastructure, and platform expansion.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Fundraising for the institutional capital raise was supported by several well-known global and regional investors, such as Impact Fund Denmark and Equitane, as well as ongoing support from the Fund for Export Development in Africa (FEDA), the impact investment fund of Afreximbank.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This round of equity investment continues the successful fundraising trend of Spiro with the most recent round of funding concentrated around the $100 million mark in late 2025 after having secured a debt facility of $50 million in February 2026. The latest injection edges the e-mobility pioneer significantly closer to unicorn status.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Moving Beyond Proof-of-Concept to Real Scale</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Founded by Gagan Gupta, who also serves as the Chairman of Equitane, Spiro has successfully navigated the challenging proof-of-concept phase to achieve massive infrastructure scale. While most international EV companies encounter difficulties with capital-intensive rollouts, Spiro achieved a commanding market share by customising its fleet and business model to the peculiar ground-level operation of African cities.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_202167" style="width: 1034px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-202167" class="size-large wp-image-202167" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/Electric-vehicle-sign-1024x558.jpg" alt="Electric vehicle sign" width="1024" height="558" /><p id="caption-attachment-202167" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Unsplash</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company&#8217;s platform currently supports a fleet of over 100,000 active electric motorcycles and 2,500+ smart battery-swapping stations across seven rapidly growing urban markets (Kenya, Uganda, Rwanda, Nigeria, Togo, Benin &amp; Cameroon). In sum, riders have travelled more than 1 billion kilometres without emitting any carbon and performed 30 million swaps to date.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;Supported by our global pool of investors, we are entering our next growth chapter to deliver clean, cost-effective energy and transport alternatives to millions of riders across the continent,&#8221; Gupta said in a statement accompanying the announcement. He noted that the company is experiencing phenomenal momentum, tracking consecutive month-on-month sector growth of 15% to 20%.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News:</span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/endra-raises-50m-to-automate-data-centre-design/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400"> Endra Raises $50M to Automate Data Centre Design</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Rewriting the Economics of Urban Transport</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The rapid adoption of Spiro&#8217;s electric two-wheelers is primarily driven by immediate, unarguable economic benefits for riders, particularly commercial motorcycle taxi operators (</span><i><span style="font-weight: 400">boda-bodas</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400">). In major hubs like Nairobi and Kampala, fuel costs for traditional internal combustion engine (ICE) motorcycles frequently consume 40% to 60% of a driver&#8217;s daily income.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">By switching to Spiro’s electric models, operators can compress their daily mobility and energy expenses by up to 40%, pocketing net savings of roughly $2 per day. Furthermore, the company’s smart asset-tracing and connected IoT vehicle technology have dramatically reduced default risks for asset financing. Consequently, borrowing and financing rates for riders, which historically hovered between an oppressive 45% and 50%, have plummeted down to a manageable 15% to 16%.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The climate benefits are equally stark. An independent lifecycle assessment conducted in Kenya revealed that Spiro&#8217;s motorcycles achieve a 72% reduction in climate impact compared to fossil-fuel alternatives, effectively preventing approximately 19 tonnes of carbon dioxide emissions over each vehicle&#8217;s standard operational lifespan.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Deepening Local Industrialization and Energy Storage</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Spiro intends to deploy the $215 million across three core strategic pillars. First, the capital will be used to heavily densify its battery-swapping grids in existing markets to meet surging consumer demand. Second, it will bankroll the company&#8217;s imminent entry into massive new geographic markets, with the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and Ethiopia explicitly targeted next.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The third, and arguably most crucial pillar is the aggressive localisation of its industrial footprint. Rather than relying on imported kits, Spiro already runs manufacturing and assembly facilities in Kenya, Rwanda, and Uganda, alongside a dedicated battery recycling plant in Nigeria.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;Building a durable sector requires more than importing finished vehicles,&#8221; emphasised Gupta. Spiro aims to have 80% of its bike value-addition sourced locally by the first quarter of next year. On top of that, the company plans to kickstart domestic battery assembly on the continent later this year, with partner-led cell manufacturing projected to launch within 18 to 24 months.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Beyond transit, Spiro is leveraging its engineering team of over 150 specialists and 30 proprietary patents to expand into a distributed clean-energy utility network. By rolling out solar-powered swap stations and exploring second-life battery applications for stationary grid storage, the company is positioning itself to be a fundamental backbone of Africa&#8217;s broader renewable energy transition.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/spiro-raises-215m-for-africa-ev-expansion/" data-wpel-link="internal">Spiro Raises $215M for Africa EV Expansion</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
