		<title>Invisix Raises €20M to Advance AI Chip Manufacturing</title>
		<link>https://ventureburn.com/invisix-raises-e20m-to-advance-ai-chip-manufacturing/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Ekemini]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 01 Jun 2026 15:44:34 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[News]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Venture Capital]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://ventureburn.com/?p=202134</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Invisix has raised a €20 million seed funding round to accelerate the development of its next-generation chip measurement technology. Hitachi Ventures and Transition Ventures co-led the round, with imec.xpand, Doosan</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/invisix-raises-e20m-to-advance-ai-chip-manufacturing/" data-wpel-link="internal">Invisix Raises €20M to Advance AI Chip Manufacturing</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://invisix.nl/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">Invisix </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">has raised a €20 million seed </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/xcena-raises-135m-series-b-for-memory-centric-computing/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">funding </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">round to accelerate the development of its next-generation chip measurement technology. </span>Hitachi Ventures and Transition Ventures co-led the round, with imec.xpand, Doosan Investment Co., and an undisclosed semiconductor manufacturer participating.</p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Solving the Blind Spot of the AI Era</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Traditional optical inspection and metrology (the science of microscopic measurement) use conventional lasers to illuminate wafers during production. </span>As the world enters sub-2-nanometre nodes and GAA transistor structures, chip features will exceed visible light wavelength limits, preventing proper light penetration.</p>
<div>
<div data-test-render-count="1">
<div class="group">
<div class="contents">
<div class="group relative relative pb-3" data-is-streaming="false">
<div class="font-claude-response relative leading-[1.65rem] [&amp;_pre&gt;div]:bg-bg-000/50 [&amp;_pre&gt;div]:border-0.5 [&amp;_pre&gt;div]:border-border-400 [&amp;_.ignore-pre-bg&gt;div]:bg-transparent [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.standard-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pl-2 [&amp;_.progressive-markdown_:is(p,blockquote,ul,ol,h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6)]:pr-8">
<div class="standard-markdown grid-cols-1 grid [&amp;_&gt;_*]:min-w-0 gap-3 standard-markdown">
<p>Slow, destructive imaging alternatives like transmission electron microscopy (TEM) currently force chipmakers to compromise their processes. This requires cutting a microscopic cross-section out of a multimillion-dollar silicon wafer to look inside, a process that ruins the sample and takes hours, ruining any chance of real-time quality control on a high-volume assembly line.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id="attachment_202138" style="width: 1034px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-202138" class="size-large wp-image-202138" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/AI-chip-1024x576.jpg" alt="AI chip" width="1024" height="576" /><p id="caption-attachment-202138" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Unsplash</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Invisix solves this visibility deficit by swapping traditional laser light for soft X-rays. Operating at wavelengths between 0.1 nm and 10 nm, soft X-rays easily pierce through dense layers of silicon to illuminate buried nanoscale structures without damaging them.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;Semiconductor manufacturers can&#8217;t build what they can&#8217;t see,&#8221; explained Dr. Christina Porter, co-founder and CEO of Invisix, in a statement accompanying the announcement. &#8220;As chips become completely three-dimensional, the industry needs a new generation of metrology tools that can look inside these incredibly miniature structures without destroying them.&#8221;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/xcena-raises-135m-series-b-for-memory-centric-computing/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">XCENA Raises $135M Series B for Memory-Centric Computing</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Nobel Prize-Winning Physics Meets Industrial Scaling</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The underlying architecture of Invisix’s system relies on High Harmonic Generation (HHG), a highly advanced optical breakthrough rooted directly in the breakthroughs recognised by the 2023 Nobel Prize in Physics.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The system utilises an ultra-fast, short-pulsed drive laser to fire focused light into noble gas atoms, exciting them into an ultra-high energy state. When these atoms snap back to equilibrium, they emit high-frequency, broadband soft X-ray light spanning multiple colours simultaneously.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Unlike a standard single-wavelength laser, this broad spectrum of light captures a far richer 3D scattering pattern when it strikes a wafer. Invisix’s proprietary reconstruction algorithms and machine-learning models then process this raw acoustic and wave-scatter data, assembling a flawless, layer-by-layer 3D digital twin of the chip&#8217;s internal structure in near real-time.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">A Decade of ASML Pedigree</span></h2>
<p>Investors note that a €20 million seed round is historically massive for a deep-tech hardware startup, but view the company as uniquely de-risked. Invisix was founded by ASML alumni and PhD physicists Dr. Christina Porter and Sietse van der Post, who serves as CTO. The technology wasn&#8217;t built from scratch; it was incubated inside ASML&#8217;s core R&amp;D pipeline for over a decade.</p>
<p>ASML focuses on immediate feedback loops for scanner performance, but spun out Invisix to pursue broader factory-wide process control and yield monitoring. The team has already publicly validated its thesis through collaborative data disclosures with Intel and imec. Invisix demonstrated that its soft X-ray scatterometry successfully mapped hidden defects inside GAA transistor architectures, one of semiconductor manufacturing&#8217;s most complex targets.</p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Next Steps: Moving into the Cleanroom</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The €20 million influx of capital will be used to scale operations at the company’s headquarters in Eindhoven, the epicentre of Europe&#8217;s semiconductor supply chain. Invisix recently completed the relocation of its 300mm-wafer-capable soft X-ray test bench to a brand-new, state-of-the-art cleanroom facility.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company will utilise the funding to double down on engineering talent and accelerate the development of its very first production-ready, shippable commercial system. Concurrently, the Eindhoven cleanroom will act as a live testing ground for global foundry clients looking to run high-throughput demonstrations on their own experimental 2-nanometre and 1.4-nanometre silicon wafers.</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/invisix-raises-e20m-to-advance-ai-chip-manufacturing/" data-wpel-link="internal">Invisix Raises €20M to Advance AI Chip Manufacturing</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
			</item>
